A jury recommended life without parole for a man found guilty of causing a train crash that killed 11 in Los Angeles.
The defendant, Juan Manuel Alvarez, apologized for the disaster, claiming he was trying to kill himself.
Prosecutors allege he staged the accident for attention from his wife.
Alvarez's troubled childhood and methamphetamine addiction were highlighted in his defense.
The trial revealed his history of suicide attempts and delusions.
The jury is deliberating between life in prison or the death penalty.
Family members and psychiatrists are expected to testify in his favor.
Alvarez's mother shared heartbreaking accounts of abuse suffered at the hands of her husband.
